1
00:00:00,233 --> 00:00:29,396
Namo tassa bhagavato harahato samma sambuddhassa Namo tassa bhagavato harahato samma sambuddhassa Namo tassa bhagavato harahato samma sambuddhassa Homage to the Buddha, the Blessed Noble

2
00:00:29,663 --> 00:00:35,209
and fully Self-Awakened One.

3
00:00:35,228 --> 00:00:38,353
So there's quite a bit to get through really for an evening.

4
00:00:42,957 --> 00:00:46,322
I just want to cover at least three areas.

5
00:00:46,381 --> 00:00:55,451
The first one is, you know, to revise and for some of you it may become anew the teaching of the Buddha on how we condition ourselves.

6
00:00:57,186 --> 00:01:00,171
And then to talk a bit about metta and what we call the illimitables.

7
00:01:01,613 --> 00:01:06,903
And then finally to say something about forgiveness which we'll be practicing tomorrow.

8
00:01:09,447 --> 00:01:16,537
There are two things about the Buddhist teaching in terms of our conditioning.

9
00:01:17,700 --> 00:01:22,688
All our conditioning is self-made.

10
00:01:23,831 --> 00:01:51,492
and that's a bit difficult to sort of grasp at first but all the information and all the experiences that you have in the world come at you as it were and there's an inner process where you begin to react to it within yourself and create the conditionings that you end up with

11
00:01:51,861 --> 00:02:07,734
So all these things that we tend to suffer from, the depression, anxiety, all that sort of stuff, and on the positive side, over-excitement, indulgence, all that, all that part is actually self-created.

12
00:02:07,795 --> 00:02:17,924
You can go further and say that the whole world is self-created if you include your body, because your body filters out what comes in.

13
00:02:18,743 --> 00:02:21,766
So if you're blind, you obviously don't live in a visual universe.

14
00:02:22,895 --> 00:02:29,104
And then of course the society you live in also filters things out by its own prejudices.

15
00:02:30,306 --> 00:02:47,231
But everything that comes to us is then worked upon within ourselves and although people influence us and our society influences us, the very language influences us, the fact is that we end up creating our own worlds.

16
00:02:47,431 --> 00:03:07,210
Even here now you see in this room, Theravada Buddhism isn't an idealism, it doesn't say that this room doesn't exist, like when we all walk out it doesn't disappear, it has its own reality, inverted commas, but it does say that the room that we experience is peculiar to us.

17
00:03:07,751 --> 00:03:17,099
So actually speaking, there are ten different rooms here, because each one of us has a different perspective on it, different feeling about it, and so on.

18
00:03:18,480 --> 00:03:23,188
And in that way you begin to understand that we're actually living in our own world.

19
00:03:24,390 --> 00:03:27,336
And they're parallel, sort of.

20
00:03:29,078 --> 00:03:30,700
They're not always harmonious.

21
00:03:31,141 --> 00:03:40,336
But when we realize that we're living in our own world, then of course the accent then is to throw the responsibility upon us to do something about it.

22
00:03:41,278 --> 00:03:43,002
So that gets rid of all blame.

23
00:03:43,342 --> 00:03:44,344
So you can't blame.

24
00:03:44,866 --> 00:04:00,537
And there comes a point of, shall we say, maturity where you realize that you can't continue to blame your parents, your society and all the rest of it for the state of mind that you actually have to bear with.

25
00:04:01,782 --> 00:04:14,093
And that taking a personal responsibility about oneself is actually the true beginning of the spiritual path because that's beginning to take a hold of your life.

26
00:04:14,114 --> 00:04:20,440
That's the beginning where you decide what changes you're going to make and how you're going to make them.

27
00:04:20,880 --> 00:04:23,824
And this metta-practice that we're doing is part and parcel of that.

28
00:04:25,406 --> 00:04:26,906
So where does that begin, you see?

29
00:04:26,947 --> 00:04:28,288
Where does that process begin?

30
00:04:28,348 --> 00:04:31,451
It begins with an intention.

31
00:04:31,920 --> 00:04:46,576
That's why, for those of you who've practiced Vipassana, seeing your intentions is that crucial point where you have the space to see whether this intention is wholesome or unwholesome, whether it's doing you any good or not.

32
00:04:46,596 --> 00:04:51,541
And it's in that little space that you can say, no, I won't go down there, or yes, I will.

33
00:04:52,622 --> 00:04:59,649
If for one moment you lose that moment of intention, it very quickly moves into identification.

34
00:05:00,389 --> 00:05:03,653
So what was a wanting becomes I want.

35
00:05:04,153 --> 00:05:09,401
And at that point, really, it's virtually impossible to stop the action flowing out from the intention.

36
00:05:10,963 --> 00:05:20,759
So every time, you see, you walk past Costa Coffee and Starbucks and the coffee grabs hold of your nose, see, there's want, you see.

37
00:05:21,439 --> 00:05:27,949
If you're not quick enough, you're in there, having a cup of coffee, whether you liked it or not, whether you wanted it or not, whether you needed it or not.

38
00:05:28,250 --> 00:05:34,502
And it's those habitual actions that we get caught up in that we have to come back on.

39
00:05:35,084 --> 00:05:41,617
And the way we do it is by having this very sharp mindfulness to see intentions as it arises.

40
00:05:43,706 --> 00:05:47,413
So the role of intention is crucial in our conditioning.

41
00:05:48,194 --> 00:05:55,786
The next step that we've already touched upon is the process of it being brought from a potential into an actual.

42
00:05:56,487 --> 00:06:01,656
So if I stand outside Costa Coffee thinking I'd like a cup of coffee, nothing's happening.

43
00:06:02,197 --> 00:06:08,127
That's the power of that old conditioning of wanting coffee.

44
00:06:08,108 --> 00:06:14,540
And as long as I stay there with it, no matter how uncomfortable it may feel, actually nothing's happening.

45
00:06:15,100 --> 00:06:17,365
Nothing's happening in terms of it being developed.

46
00:06:18,166 --> 00:06:26,161
But if we stay with that and wait for it to die away, then some energy within that conditioning has been released.

47
00:06:26,180 --> 00:06:30,910
Some energy has been destroyed because it's not been re-empowered.

48
00:06:31,278 --> 00:06:47,797
So there is a moment when having decided to, having had the intention come up to have this coffee, there's a moment of impulsion, there's a moment where an energy goes into that intention and it manifests.

49
00:06:47,817 --> 00:06:48,898
That energy is your will.

50
00:06:50,338 --> 00:06:54,483
And the Buddha goes as far as to say that it is will that he calls action.

51
00:06:54,817 --> 00:06:58,228
So what you do is not so important, but how you do.

52
00:06:58,447 --> 00:07:01,576
You know, it ain't what you do, it's the way that you do it.

53
00:07:01,596 --> 00:07:03,903
You know that one?

54
00:07:03,923 --> 00:07:06,651
So it's a case of catching the intention

55
00:07:07,357 --> 00:07:15,327
and holding it so that you don't fall immediately into willing it whereby you reinforce that old habitual action.

56
00:07:17,350 --> 00:07:32,672
So that's a sort of crucial understanding in terms of the Buddha's psychology and it comes in those of you who know the psychology of dependence origination where he's putting his finger very clearly

57
00:07:32,651 --> 00:07:34,720
on where the problem lies.

58
00:07:35,401 --> 00:07:41,463
It lies at that point of tanha, some of you will know that word, of desire.

59
00:07:42,625 --> 00:07:48,774
These words that come from Scripture, translated from one language to another, is always difficult.

60
00:07:49,053 --> 00:07:55,564
And it's translated normally as craving, which seems to me always a little bit over the top, because sometimes you just want it and you just do it.

61
00:07:55,584 --> 00:07:58,067
You can't sort of label it as craving.

62
00:07:58,086 --> 00:08:06,759
But what they're trying to do in these translations is distinguish between a desire and intention which is wholesome and one which is unwholesome.

63
00:08:08,291 --> 00:08:19,612
So there is a word in the Buddha's language which is also translated as desire but there's a choice of it being wholesome or unwholesome.

64
00:08:20,334 --> 00:08:27,447
Whereas this other word that you get in depen origination is always unwholesome because it's always coming from the self.

65
00:08:27,529 --> 00:08:39,322
Now, this self that we talk about, the teaching about not-self, it's not a, you have to be careful, it's not a denial, it's not a metaphysical proposition.

66
00:08:39,763 --> 00:08:41,585
The Buddha's not saying, there is no self.

67
00:08:42,264 --> 00:08:43,306
It's a teaching tool.

68
00:08:43,506 --> 00:08:51,715
He's saying, whatever you experience, if it's arising and passing away, how can it be you?

69
00:08:52,774 --> 00:09:03,847
And it's that way of looking at things that begins to make you realize that all these things that you've identified with are actually immaterial, they're not substantial.

70
00:09:04,389 --> 00:09:08,693
They don't account to anything, any substance in the universe.

71
00:09:09,214 --> 00:09:10,775
So we're in this flow of events.

72
00:09:11,356 --> 00:09:13,779
And it's most obvious is this body, you know.

73
00:09:14,259 --> 00:09:16,722
I mean, this isn't the body we were born with.

74
00:09:16,702 --> 00:09:22,014
It may have a sort of regular blueprint running through it, but it definitely is not the same body.

75
00:09:22,735 --> 00:09:25,062
And if we're to believe it, it's not the same body we had seven years ago.

76
00:09:25,682 --> 00:09:31,134
So next time you look in the mirror, you see, look in your eye and say, now you weren't here seven years ago.

77
00:09:32,009 --> 00:09:40,624
and just keep acknowledging the fact that the body itself is in a constant process of change, and yet we identify with it in very deep ways, you know.

78
00:09:41,144 --> 00:09:44,049
So when death approaches, it's sort of freak-out time.

79
00:09:44,070 --> 00:09:52,465
And that freaking out, that terrible shock that comes when it's our turn to go, is the measure of that attachment, is the measure of that identity, you see.

80
00:09:54,149 --> 00:10:05,041
So this tanha is those desires which come from wrong understanding, those desires which arise out of greed and hatred.

81
00:10:05,120 --> 00:10:11,126
Greed here is that whole business of acquisition, and hatred is that whole business of aversion.

82
00:10:11,687 --> 00:10:17,254
Actually it's translated as aversion, because again we don't have a word which...

83
00:10:17,234 --> 00:10:45,705
grasp the total meaning of the original Pali word but it also includes fear when you come across something which is threatening you you either want to obliterate it, annihilate it if it's too big you run for it so you've always got this fight and flight syndrome and that's included in this word so whenever you hear people talk about greed and aversion this aversion includes the fear that we have

84
00:10:47,643 --> 00:11:10,798
So understanding the role of intention in the process of our psychology and understanding that nothing actually happens until we empower it, until we actually do something, either as a train of thoughts or a process of speech or an action, has it got a conditioning effect?

85
00:11:10,778 --> 00:11:37,883
if we don't empower an intention then the energy with which it comes is just allowed to dissipate and that's basically how you get rid of habits and mental states that you don't want and that's through that we learn very clearly through the process of Vipassana but it's something you take out into daily life it's not just something you do on the sitting stool yeah

86
00:11:38,335 --> 00:11:48,530
Whenever something negative comes up, it's the acknowledgement of it and just bearing with it, acknowledging it, feeling it, but not doing anything.

87
00:11:48,630 --> 00:11:54,639
That's the point, not doing anything and just allowing it to dissipate, the energy dissipate.

88
00:11:57,386 --> 00:12:04,457
Now here of course we have another thing that we're doing, which is the good side of desire, which is coming from another center.

89
00:12:04,717 --> 00:12:06,019
That's the important thing to understand.

90
00:12:06,480 --> 00:12:18,720
There is within us a different center, call it Buddha, call it your wisdom center, doesn't matter what you call it, but it's coming from a different place than the one which is self-seeking.

91
00:12:18,885 --> 00:12:23,038
And metta is what you're developing from that center.

92
00:12:25,326 --> 00:12:30,380
And it's important if you practice vipassana always to do metta.

93
00:12:30,783 --> 00:12:46,212
Although in, say, the Zen tradition, they'll say that compassion arises naturally with wisdom, which is true, which is true, but it does help to have a practice which, as it were, just eggs that little movement on.

94
00:12:46,894 --> 00:12:50,421
And in the Buddhist teaching, we've got this eightfold path.

95
00:12:50,480 --> 00:12:52,605
And the first one is this right understanding.

96
00:12:53,581 --> 00:13:12,855
it's in right understanding that vipassana is placed so vipassana is seeing things as they really are and then there has to be this attitudinal change it has to drop systemically it's a systemic movement from understanding into the heart as an attitude

97
00:13:12,835 --> 00:13:20,745
And that's where it begins then to manifest outward through your thought and your speech and your actions.

98
00:13:20,966 --> 00:13:22,587
And that's your next steps.

99
00:13:22,607 --> 00:13:25,071
Right speech, right action, right livelihood.

100
00:13:25,831 --> 00:13:29,977
If it stops anywhere on that path, then the spiritual life gets stilted.

101
00:13:30,057 --> 00:13:33,121
It becomes sort of twisted.

102
00:13:34,097 --> 00:13:59,008
People who practice vipassanā without metta, the danger is that this aloofness that you must have in vipassanā, this equanimity which, as it were, you find from that observation post within yourself, where you can feel and see things and you're watching things, very quickly or very, shall we say, the danger is it slips into indifference.

103
00:14:00,052 --> 00:14:27,831
and once it becomes indifference then it moves to callousness and basically you've lost the path so somehow to keep this equanimity there has to be another practice which re-engages that observer within you into the psycho-physical organism and then into the world and that's what Metta does it helps you to re-engage

104
00:14:29,852 --> 00:14:32,552
Can I ask a question?

105
00:14:32,573 --> 00:14:34,750
Would Santa have that effect as well?

106
00:14:35,269 --> 00:14:37,634
Samatha is slightly different.

107
00:14:37,673 --> 00:14:46,486
This is a Samatha practice, but it's more pointed to the outflow, to the engagement, you see, the illimitables.

108
00:14:47,268 --> 00:15:01,750
Samatha itself is really more to do with us finding this calmness, this peace within us, which again is a great help, and it's definitely of advantage if you're going to do the pāsanā, to have that easy basis

109
00:15:01,730 --> 00:15:05,476
of entering into a very quiet, relaxed, focused state.

110
00:15:08,202 --> 00:15:11,509
But it's not necessary in itself to do vipassana.

111
00:15:12,711 --> 00:15:19,705
And again, samatha, just like this practice, can become very selfish.

112
00:15:20,123 --> 00:15:24,548
you can practice this to the point where you begin to really get blissed out.

113
00:15:25,529 --> 00:15:35,922
And one of the things about doing that is that you realize that these internal blissful states are not dependent on anything out there.

114
00:15:36,582 --> 00:15:46,434
Then you begin to understand why people can just live in rags, live under trees, eat what they're given, because it doesn't matter anymore, because their bliss is within them.

115
00:15:47,308 --> 00:16:06,567
the problem with that of course is that it's not connected to the world so when such a person enters the world and stands on their foot an enormous amount of anger can arise and that's the danger of doing something like this without the purification process of vipassana now

116
00:16:07,272 --> 00:16:19,423
living in ordinary daily life, living in the world, that really becomes impossible because you have to engage with people.

117
00:16:19,744 --> 00:16:21,566
So you have to put this into practice.

118
00:16:22,407 --> 00:16:24,589
And the heart will grow quite naturally with that.

119
00:16:24,788 --> 00:16:30,774
And it actually, to my mind, grows much better because of that interconnectedness, you see.

120
00:16:31,895 --> 00:16:34,578
So we'll come to that a little bit later, I think.

121
00:16:37,427 --> 00:16:39,931
Samatha, there's two types of meditation.

122
00:16:40,692 --> 00:16:45,177
Vipassana is this investigation of ourselves.

123
00:16:46,437 --> 00:16:51,904
And the Samatha practice is to do with establishing, creating and establishing beautiful states of mind.

124
00:16:53,706 --> 00:16:58,913
So I'm sure you've heard of people looking at candles and breathing.

125
00:16:58,994 --> 00:17:00,876
I have, you know, regulated breathing.

126
00:17:01,518 --> 00:17:06,223
All those are little tricks to get this very one-pointed singleness of attention.

127
00:17:06,684 --> 00:17:12,712
And the mind becomes like a focus, like a laser beam, you see.

128
00:17:13,314 --> 00:17:15,597
And it creates this lovely energy within you.

129
00:17:16,778 --> 00:17:17,339
Is that like what mantra is?

130
00:17:17,641 --> 00:17:18,943
Yeah, mantras are the same.

131
00:17:19,724 --> 00:17:20,266
Anything like that.

132
00:17:21,188 --> 00:17:26,680
Coloured circles, gazing upon the beloved's face, all that sort of stuff.

133
00:17:26,839 --> 00:17:28,923
Anything which produces a beautiful state.

134
00:17:28,943 --> 00:17:37,422
But remember, if that beautiful state is dependent on something out there, then that something out there always has to be there for this to arise.

135
00:17:38,313 --> 00:18:00,202
it's created from within ourselves then of course it's always there when we want it you see and that's the difference between what you might say is a worldly practice as opposed to a spiritual one so now recognizing metta

136
00:18:00,942 --> 00:18:30,492
as a practice which re-engages us both with ourselves it re-engages with ourselves and through ourselves into the world we have to be clear as to what this matter is and we touched upon it yesterday so it's an attitude now attitudes pre-exist emotions it's the heart's way of relating to something and then the heart as it were begins to resonate

137
00:18:30,742 --> 00:18:59,619
and that's what we call an emotion or that's the emotional feeling part of the attitude but the attitude is prior to that now during your practice you will have been moving from that attitude of wishing people well but your heart isn't responding you know it just feels tired or fed up and then you realize ah you see this attitude is coming from somewhere behind or before

138
00:18:59,599 --> 00:19:01,461
the heart actually begins to resonate.

139
00:19:03,904 --> 00:19:11,374
And the big mistake is to confuse those lovely feelings with goodwill.

140
00:19:12,094 --> 00:19:18,221
Because then you make the mistake of thinking, I'm not practicing goodwill unless I feel loving.

141
00:19:18,902 --> 00:19:19,722
You see?

142
00:19:19,742 --> 00:19:27,352
And that's where we get confused with an emotion and the actual attitudinal state, which is being in a state of goodwill with people.

143
00:19:28,173 --> 00:19:28,272
Yeah?

144
00:19:29,484 --> 00:19:34,471
So you can see this is very different from love which arises from attachments.

145
00:19:35,773 --> 00:19:37,877
So you have to be very careful here.

146
00:19:38,638 --> 00:19:41,242
Attachments gets a bad name in Buddhism.

147
00:19:41,282 --> 00:19:47,151
But you have to make a distinction between something which is unskillful or unwholesome and something which is evil.

148
00:19:49,295 --> 00:19:52,859
Attachments aren't evil in the sense like murdering somebody.

149
00:19:53,481 --> 00:19:56,005
but they are definitely unwholesome.

150
00:19:56,025 --> 00:20:01,512
So an attachment, say, a parent, a mother, to a child is absolutely natural.

151
00:20:01,553 --> 00:20:06,519
I can't imagine a mother not having an attachment to their child.

152
00:20:07,760 --> 00:20:19,978
But what happens is, of course, is that attachment puts a certain pressure on the child, because the attachment is always wanting the child to be as the mother would want the child to be.

153
00:20:19,958 --> 00:20:27,365
and that's where the problem lies and that's why you get kicked back at teenage because of that contradiction.

154
00:20:28,047 --> 00:20:48,430
Now to separate out the pure love that the mother has which she also has for the child from the attachment is very difficult but it's there and the wise person will slowly distinguish between the one and the other knowing that the one is actually turning the person into an object

155
00:20:48,982 --> 00:20:50,426
And that's what an attachment does.

156
00:20:51,368 --> 00:20:57,306
Every time you do something out of an attachment, that person is being used to please you.

157
00:20:57,346 --> 00:20:59,009
They become an object.

158
00:20:59,431 --> 00:21:00,534
They've lost their humanity.

159
00:21:01,616 --> 00:21:04,865
No matter how little it is, you're dehumanizing them.

160
00:21:04,998 --> 00:21:12,073
So the way that you overcome the attachment is always to be open to their point of view, to their state.

161
00:21:12,854 --> 00:21:18,045
And that stepping into their consciousness, their way of looking at life, is the act of love.

162
00:21:18,506 --> 00:21:20,289
That is the act of compassion, you see.

163
00:21:22,413 --> 00:21:42,395
And it's obvious, so attachment, you know, it has a bad name, but it's not to be seen as evil, it's just to be seen as a consequence of delusion, of the way that we are relating to the world that we're in.

164
00:21:42,375 --> 00:21:52,248
And it's a case of recognizing it, recognizing what we're doing when we're with friends, when we're with our relatives and so on.

165
00:21:54,490 --> 00:21:57,074
When you see them, just ask them, what do you want?

166
00:21:57,394 --> 00:21:59,136
What do you want from them?

167
00:21:59,176 --> 00:22:08,248
There's your desire coming from some place where they have to feed, feed into your lack.

168
00:22:09,038 --> 00:22:19,808
And this word lack is a very, it's often used as a translation for dukkha, which means, which is translated as unsatisfactoriness or as suffering.

169
00:22:20,549 --> 00:22:28,719
But what this word lack tells us is that there's an emptiness there and we're seeking to fill the emptiness with things from the outside world.

170
00:22:30,019 --> 00:22:32,682
And of course they don't deliver, they don't deliver.

171
00:22:33,742 --> 00:22:42,557
So the word attachment in a sense is, it's a one-way process, and in fact the word connection is...

172
00:22:42,577 --> 00:22:42,798
Both.

173
00:22:43,138 --> 00:22:43,460
Both.

174
00:22:43,539 --> 00:22:45,523
That's right.

175
00:22:45,604 --> 00:22:56,663
And as I say, you connect by being open to the other, by just listening full-heartedly, open-heartedly, what the other has to say, and so on.

176
00:22:56,643 --> 00:23:12,926
and that cuts through, you see, and then of course you can feel perhaps a certain disappointment or a certain frustration or a certain fear when the person is not going to feed into your emptiness, you see.

177
00:23:13,366 --> 00:23:20,877
So that's the bad emptiness, that's not the emptiness of Mahayana, that's something else.

178
00:23:22,849 --> 00:23:25,413
So you can see it's also not romance.

179
00:23:25,673 --> 00:23:26,295
See?

180
00:23:26,315 --> 00:23:27,957
Romance is very specific, isn't it?

181
00:23:27,977 --> 00:23:30,340
You can't fall in love with anybody and everybody.

182
00:23:30,800 --> 00:23:33,664
And that is also a form of attachment.

183
00:23:33,705 --> 00:23:39,653
That's the joy, that's the deliciousness of two personalities meeting at that point.

184
00:23:40,335 --> 00:23:41,557
And it's very delicious, you know?

185
00:23:41,916 --> 00:23:47,545
But as you know, it's often three months down the line you wonder what the hell you were doing.

186
00:23:47,585 --> 00:23:50,088
There's a lot of faded...

187
00:23:52,211 --> 00:23:59,978
And then there's, and of course, but it starts there, remember, and of course if the relationship develops, and of course it develops into a true love.

188
00:24:01,138 --> 00:24:12,630
And it's obviously not erotic love, but that's very flimsy and transient and empty.

189
00:24:13,750 --> 00:24:22,000
If you just practice making love just for making love, it becomes an empty experience because the whole of the human being is not involved.

190
00:24:22,599 --> 00:24:23,922
Basically, it's a prostitution.

191
00:24:25,583 --> 00:24:28,445
And I always love Woody Allen's little comment on this.

192
00:24:29,792 --> 00:24:43,212
He says sexual pleasure by itself is an empty thing, is an empty experience, but as empty experiences go.

193
00:24:48,280 --> 00:24:50,483
So what is this metta then, you see?

194
00:24:51,144 --> 00:24:56,593
Well, just ask yourself, what would you want from a good friend?

195
00:24:57,468 --> 00:25:01,292
And just as those qualities come to you, then that's what metta is.

196
00:25:02,753 --> 00:25:14,909
Whatever companionship, open-heartedness, and so on, all the pleasant things that you would want of a good and close friend, that's metta.

197
00:25:15,609 --> 00:25:16,049
That's all it is.

198
00:25:16,451 --> 00:25:19,914
And metta is actually connected to the word mitra, which means friend.

199
00:25:21,311 --> 00:25:30,400
Now you can see this metta is your basic relationship to all sentient beings.

200
00:25:31,039 --> 00:25:38,666
Last night we practiced that awareness of just relaxing into the present moment.

201
00:25:38,967 --> 00:25:41,249
And I pointed that out as your default position.

202
00:25:41,848 --> 00:25:49,256
If we can keep coming back to that state of just being in the present moment with an empty mind, what do I mean by that?

203
00:25:49,296 --> 00:25:50,896
I mean no thought.

204
00:25:52,041 --> 00:25:57,291
When you hear in Zen, no mind, they don't mean that you've lost it.

205
00:25:58,193 --> 00:25:59,576
They just mean no thought.

206
00:26:00,538 --> 00:26:15,045
So if you can bring yourself every so often during the day, not just that meditation, but every day, just to sort of collapse, as it were, just draw yourself into the present moment, and you do that, I find the easiest way to do that is by putting my attention on hearing.

207
00:26:15,768 --> 00:26:19,574
Just by putting my attention on hearing, I immediately come into the present moment.

208
00:26:20,115 --> 00:26:23,540
And because I'm hearing and listening, I'm not responding.

209
00:26:24,261 --> 00:26:26,766
So it's a position of real equanimity.

210
00:26:26,786 --> 00:26:29,009
It's a position where I'm very open.

211
00:26:30,092 --> 00:26:37,844
And the other trick I found was to put your attention on the left side of the body.

212
00:26:38,645 --> 00:26:40,729
Your right eye on your left side of the body.

213
00:26:40,709 --> 00:26:41,829
And that cuts out speech.

214
00:26:42,290 --> 00:26:46,516
It draws energy from the speech center of your brain.

215
00:26:46,756 --> 00:26:47,778
It's quite magic, actually.

216
00:26:47,938 --> 00:26:49,118
You'll be surprised.

217
00:26:49,138 --> 00:26:49,900
It'll stop you talking.

218
00:26:50,540 --> 00:27:05,940
So, if we consider that to be the default position of the whole of our lives, out of which we rise, out of which we can see an intention, know it to be wholesome, and then to move into action, right?

219
00:27:06,190 --> 00:27:14,097
The default position in terms of our relationship to sentient beings, but specifically to human beings, is this meta.

220
00:27:15,019 --> 00:27:19,583
Because it's from that basic position that the other two illimitables arise.

221
00:27:22,286 --> 00:27:26,670
If you have a friend and they fall into bad times, you naturally want to help them.

222
00:27:27,451 --> 00:27:28,291
It's not a problem, is it?

223
00:27:28,311 --> 00:27:31,454
It just rises naturally out of your friendship.

224
00:27:31,654 --> 00:27:37,448
And if your friend has good fortune and is happy, you're naturally happy for them.

225
00:27:38,230 --> 00:27:46,828
So sympathetic joy, reciprocal joy, all that joy in other people's joy arises naturally.

226
00:27:46,929 --> 00:27:49,173
You don't have to work at it.

227
00:27:49,508 --> 00:27:52,335
So that's why the Buddha really pushes this matter.

228
00:27:53,096 --> 00:27:58,368
I know that in later Buddhism they began to develop much more the idea of compassion.

229
00:27:59,451 --> 00:28:03,279
One can understand that because the Buddha's teaching is about suffering and the end of suffering.

230
00:28:03,300 --> 00:28:08,192
So the end of suffering, wanting to put an end to suffering, is compassion.

231
00:28:09,521 --> 00:28:16,635
But in his original teachings, as it comes out in the original scriptures, he's very much into this metta as a way.

232
00:28:16,936 --> 00:28:20,503
And the discourse on metta really lays it out.

233
00:28:20,663 --> 00:28:27,919
And he's asking us to constantly develop that attitude throughout the whole day.

234
00:28:28,337 --> 00:28:42,221
whenever we have a moment of time, and think of how much time we have when you consider things like going from here to there, or waiting for a bus, or waiting at the lights, or climbing up stairs, or waiting for a friend.

235
00:28:42,603 --> 00:28:48,472
If you add all those little bits together by the end of the day, I think they come out to a couple of hours frankly,

236
00:28:48,452 --> 00:28:55,019
And what we do is we just tend to let the mind wander, let the mind go here and there and just complete waste of mental energy.

237
00:28:55,701 --> 00:29:01,627
It's during those times that you can bring these thoughts to mind and it has that effect.

238
00:29:02,008 --> 00:29:05,192
It's constantly developing this heart of goodwill.

239
00:29:13,540 --> 00:29:14,342
You would be.

240
00:29:15,048 --> 00:29:15,808
That's what I'm saying.

241
00:29:16,671 --> 00:29:17,933
It's a natural thing.

242
00:29:18,654 --> 00:29:31,339
No, what I'm saying is that once the base of metta is there, and you have a friendship with somebody, then you can understand that you don't have to try and be compassionate.

243
00:29:31,881 --> 00:29:34,486
It just arises naturally when you see them in a bad state.

244
00:29:34,926 --> 00:29:36,229
You want to help.

245
00:29:37,558 --> 00:29:45,375
So, these are called illimitable because there's meant to be innumerable number of beings

246
00:29:45,540 --> 00:29:49,825
But more interestingly, it's a bit like numbers.

247
00:29:50,125 --> 00:29:51,146
You can always add ones.

248
00:29:51,426 --> 00:29:54,549
No matter how big your number is, you can always say, and one.

249
00:29:55,089 --> 00:29:58,093
So it's the same with love, compassion, joy, equanimity.

250
00:29:58,594 --> 00:30:00,915
Their development is indefinite.

251
00:30:01,217 --> 00:30:05,180
You just keep on developing it, developing it, so long as you're awake.

252
00:30:06,301 --> 00:30:10,806
And in fact it says that, so long as you're awake, develop this attitude, you see.

253
00:30:12,845 --> 00:30:19,996
Now, we haven't practiced the compassionate part, but basically it's very simple.

254
00:30:20,036 --> 00:30:26,484
You bring to mind people whom you know are suffering, and the phrase is, may you be free of suffering.

255
00:30:26,826 --> 00:30:28,327
It's as simple as that.

256
00:30:28,347 --> 00:30:29,890
And with joy, may you be joyful.

257
00:30:30,050 --> 00:30:31,393
May you continue to be joyful.

258
00:30:31,413 --> 00:30:32,654
May your joy increase.

259
00:30:34,517 --> 00:30:37,622
We can't do that this weekend because we don't have the time for it.

260
00:30:37,642 --> 00:30:38,363
But you might...

261
00:30:38,630 --> 00:30:43,054
You might add it on to one of your blessings, if you wish.

262
00:30:43,253 --> 00:30:43,974
Completely up to you.

263
00:30:45,376 --> 00:30:53,785
But at this stage, I would really suggest that you keep it just as pure metta, because, as I say, these other two things arise naturally.

264
00:30:53,805 --> 00:31:04,434
Now, just as metta has its dark enemy, what's called its close enemy, as attachment, compassion has a close enemy too, and that's grief.

265
00:31:05,291 --> 00:31:11,958
We very quickly fall into a grief for somebody, pity for somebody, instead of what compassion is.

266
00:31:12,999 --> 00:31:21,286
And again, that grief comes with attachment because this person fulfills a role in your life.

267
00:31:21,666 --> 00:31:23,508
And when they go, it leaves a gaping hole.

268
00:31:24,229 --> 00:31:33,416
Whether they fall into misfortune or whether they die or something like that, you're left with this sore within your heart.

269
00:31:34,278 --> 00:31:35,298
And that's your grief.

270
00:31:35,278 --> 00:31:39,964
But compassion is actually a joyful emotion.

271
00:31:41,165 --> 00:31:45,310
It fills the heart with joy because of the help you're giving people.

272
00:31:46,471 --> 00:31:59,548
But if you still feel about some terrible suffering, like at the moment in the combat, if you feel compassion for me, you can feel great for me, but it's not because...

273
00:32:00,305 --> 00:32:25,198
No, but what I think it fills you with is a desire to do something, and that's when we get stuck with this business of impotence, where we don't realize that we only have

274
00:32:25,178 --> 00:32:53,109
two rings around us one of power where we can do something one of influence where we can get others to do something about a situation and finally there's only you know you can't do anything and if you can't do anything then the frustration arises driven by this you know the sense of grief and wanting to do something but that's actually based on a wrong appraisal of ourselves it's actually an ego thing

275
00:32:54,153 --> 00:33:08,281
And it's only when you bear with your impotence and you realize that's it, that's the only thing you can then do is offer these goodwill practices towards them.

276
00:33:09,484 --> 00:33:12,530
And that's where you overcome that first because this is what you can do.

277
00:33:14,535 --> 00:33:15,537
And hopefully it affects.

278
00:33:19,667 --> 00:33:30,557
But you'll know that grief is a subtle enemy of compassion, especially when, say, somebody dies and you grieve for them.

279
00:33:31,439 --> 00:33:38,924
And because you equate your grief with the amount of love you have for that person, you can't stop grieving.

280
00:33:39,266 --> 00:33:44,130
Because every time your grief diminishes, you think you no longer love them.

281
00:33:44,150 --> 00:33:49,454
And you get yourself into this swirl down to a deep depression.

282
00:33:49,974 --> 00:33:58,943
But when you realize that the grief you're feeling is actually the consequence of the attachment, then love allows the person to go.

283
00:33:58,963 --> 00:34:01,026
I mean, love is very liberating.

284
00:34:03,608 --> 00:34:16,101
And these are sometimes difficult for us to grasp because of that lack of distinction between compassion, love and grief.

285
00:34:19,304 --> 00:34:21,387
The obvious enemy, of course, is cruelty.

286
00:34:21,907 --> 00:34:26,474
That's why cruelty is the worst thing you can do in the Buddhist thing.

287
00:34:27,356 --> 00:34:31,041
If you're cruel, the worst of hells is reserved for you.

288
00:34:32,463 --> 00:34:36,148
You go down to the Avicii hell where you really get thumped about.

289
00:34:37,670 --> 00:34:43,539
Because cruelty is the exact opposite of what the Buddha is teaching.

290
00:34:45,005 --> 00:34:47,027
And it's the same with joy.

291
00:34:47,528 --> 00:34:58,724
Sympathetic joy also has a subtle energy and that's this excitement where actually you're getting over joyful, over excited over something.

292
00:34:59,527 --> 00:35:05,916
And to recognize that means that you don't get the aftermath of indulgence.

293
00:35:06,588 --> 00:35:09,431
So this runs right the way through just the ordinary joys of life.

294
00:35:11,572 --> 00:35:14,637
Remember that there's two things that we have to do.

295
00:35:14,677 --> 00:35:17,480
First of all, we have to take the suffering out of pain.

296
00:35:17,880 --> 00:35:19,521
So there's always going to be physical pain.

297
00:35:20,302 --> 00:35:25,768
And for as long as we're not fully liberated, there'll always be some form of emotional pain.

298
00:35:25,789 --> 00:35:27,210
But that's not suffering itself.

299
00:35:27,590 --> 00:35:30,715
Suffering comes because of our relationship to that.

300
00:35:32,076 --> 00:35:35,699
Our not wanting to be there, our aversion to it, fear of it, and so on.

301
00:35:36,844 --> 00:35:46,476
But the other side of the coin is, of course, to take the indulgence out of pleasure, the indulgence out of the joys of life.

302
00:35:46,496 --> 00:35:49,338
And if we don't do that, then we end up with the aftermath.

303
00:35:49,579 --> 00:35:52,282
While you're enjoying something, fine, it's heaven, it's not a problem.

304
00:35:53,003 --> 00:35:54,726
It's afterwards.

305
00:35:54,746 --> 00:36:05,518
Afterwards, where you get the craving for it again, the desire for it, the frustration when you can't get it, the grief when you lose it, and the underlying anxiety of losing something that you're attached to.

306
00:36:07,489 --> 00:36:11,076
I mean, that's what a lot of our insurance industry is based on.

307
00:36:11,356 --> 00:36:15,704
Like when you go to what was Dixon's, or was it now?

308
00:36:16,666 --> 00:36:17,106
I can't remember.

309
00:36:17,648 --> 00:36:19,552
Yeah, that's right.

310
00:36:20,112 --> 00:36:30,271
When they con you into buying a three-year guarantee and you fork out more money for the guarantee than you do for the electrical equipment you bought.

311
00:36:31,793 --> 00:36:31,893
Yeah.

312
00:36:36,329 --> 00:36:54,405
So the importance of metta is that it reconnects us, connects us properly to ourselves and to the world, and it's the default position, it's the sort of basic position we have for all these other beautiful mental states to arise.

313
00:36:58,907 --> 00:37:02,632
And this is underpinned because they're also called Brahma-vihara.

314
00:37:03,213 --> 00:37:05,434
And that means the dwelling place of the highest gods.

315
00:37:05,996 --> 00:37:11,681
And what we're saying by that is that it creates the beautiful mind and the bountiful heart.

316
00:37:12,262 --> 00:37:14,085
And that's how the gods live.

317
00:37:14,405 --> 00:37:16,206
You know, whether they exist or not is not a problem.

318
00:37:16,307 --> 00:37:22,974
That's the ideal, that's the idealism towards which these practices are taking us.

319
00:37:26,684 --> 00:37:29,688
And we've talked about how often we should do it.

320
00:37:29,708 --> 00:37:31,090
You should do it all the time, whenever you can.

321
00:37:31,512 --> 00:37:34,476
But especially after the passing of the sitting.

322
00:37:34,496 --> 00:37:36,760
To re-engage with the world.

323
00:37:36,960 --> 00:37:42,007
So that's the sort of meta side of things.

324
00:37:42,148 --> 00:37:46,434
And included in that, we have to practice this forgiveness.

325
00:37:47,436 --> 00:37:49,300
So now...

326
00:37:50,512 --> 00:38:14,275
going back to that original statement that all the suffering that we are experiencing is self-caused, then the things that come out through doing things which are harmful to others, harm done to us, and the harm we do to ourselves, all the suffering around that is also self-created.

327
00:38:14,693 --> 00:38:22,250
And when we realize that, it's much easier to ask for forgiveness, it's much easier to forgive, and it's much easier to forgive oneself.

328
00:38:23,373 --> 00:38:31,992
So, when we harm somebody, it creates within us a certain turbulence

329
00:38:32,394 --> 00:38:42,465
The human heart cannot see another person's suffering without itself falling into some negativity.

330
00:38:43,367 --> 00:38:46,556
And the worst one, of course, is callousness.

331
00:38:47,396 --> 00:38:50,701
where you're no longer connected to the suffering of another human being.

332
00:38:51,081 --> 00:38:55,126
And we've had that with, you know, going right back to the Nazis, right up to present day.

333
00:38:56,047 --> 00:39:05,960
As soon as you dehumanize somebody, you have the wherewithal to create enormous suffering for them, physical suffering.

334
00:39:06,621 --> 00:39:12,628
And that callousness comes back on us and it turns our hearts into stone, you know.

335
00:39:14,583 --> 00:39:23,536
So once we open up to the fact that we've done harm to somebody, then there has to be those feelings of guilt and shame.

336
00:39:24,336 --> 00:39:26,900
Guilt is the fear of consequences.

337
00:39:27,322 --> 00:39:31,648
We're not talking here about existential guilt, that I am essentially evil.

338
00:39:33,371 --> 00:39:41,603
It's more like if you do this sort of practice, if you do that sort of thing, then the comeuppance will come at some point.

339
00:39:42,324 --> 00:39:46,469
And shame, shame is just letting ourselves down, it's a loss of self-esteem.

340
00:39:47,831 --> 00:40:03,268
And when we recognize that these are the consequences of doing something which is harmful, and we actually feel the guilt, we get in contact with it, we let it manifest, and we feel the shame, the embarrassment, let it manifest, then they actually become our guardians.

341
00:40:03,289 --> 00:40:06,072
And the Buddha actually calls them our guardians of society.

342
00:40:07,282 --> 00:40:19,021
Because when we enter into, get close to an act which we feel is unwholesome, these two come back to remind us of our consequences.

343
00:40:19,041 --> 00:40:20,664
So they become our guardians.

344
00:40:22,547 --> 00:40:23,989
In the old word, they're our conscience.

345
00:40:25,231 --> 00:40:31,300
So our conscience is made up of the knowledge of what happens when you do something harmful.

346
00:40:33,793 --> 00:40:35,818
So how do we overcome that?

347
00:40:35,918 --> 00:40:52,376
Well, tomorrow we'll be practicing it, and that is just by, through the power of our own imagination, through the power of our own imaginative thinking, we just set up these internal dialogues and just bring ourselves round to asking for forgiveness.

348
00:40:54,213 --> 00:40:58,398
And then hopefully, if it's possible, to actually do it in real life.

349
00:40:58,518 --> 00:41:03,706
But often, of course, we may find that people have disappeared whom we've harmed years ago and all that.

350
00:41:04,045 --> 00:41:08,472
People die and we've still got something on our hearts that sort of rankles us.

351
00:41:09,534 --> 00:41:18,806
And then you make this insight that you don't need another person's forgiveness to be forgiven.

352
00:41:19,407 --> 00:41:21,789
That's a real important insight to have.

353
00:41:22,715 --> 00:41:34,405
What you need to do is to work with these inner states and make that attitude of wanting to be forgiven or asking for forgiveness.

354
00:41:34,425 --> 00:41:36,369
And that in itself is the forgiveness.

355
00:41:37,074 --> 00:41:52,914
When the order meets, we meet every, when there's a group of four, there has to be four monks, four nuns, when we meet every quarter, half moon, when we meet every half moon, we confess.

356
00:41:53,655 --> 00:41:58,701
And most of the transgressions of our rule are forgiven on the confession.

357
00:41:59,081 --> 00:42:02,204
There's no sort of, you know, tied to the post and whipped confession.

358
00:42:03,264 --> 00:42:07,211
It's just having stated what you've done.

359
00:42:07,351 --> 00:42:09,795
But the response is, do you see what you've done?

360
00:42:09,815 --> 00:42:11,559
In other words, do you accept what you've done?

361
00:42:12,239 --> 00:42:13,802
And your response is probably, yes, I do.

362
00:42:14,322 --> 00:42:20,733
And then the response is, do you undertake not to break that rule again?

363
00:42:20,949 --> 00:42:24,536
So there's a commitment to try and change your ways.

364
00:42:25,378 --> 00:42:36,259
So just the ability to state clearly that one has done wrong is in fact the process of self-forgiving, of being forgiven.

365
00:42:36,677 --> 00:42:57,335
if you can put it right if you've done something wrong which you can actually put right all the better then you stop the karmic flow so for instance if you said a sharp word to somebody you know and you know they're glowering they're sort of using it behind you and all that then just to go up and say look I'm sorry for that it immediately cuts the flow of that bad karma

366
00:42:57,922 --> 00:42:58,905
Very simple to do.

367
00:42:59,304 --> 00:43:04,512
But if you've got too much pride, if you feel you were righteous, you should have been even more cruel.

368
00:43:04,873 --> 00:43:06,836
And of course it just keeps going.

369
00:43:08,099 --> 00:43:08,860
There's no end to it.

370
00:43:11,605 --> 00:43:17,434
When it comes to forgiving those who hurt us, we're on the receiving end.

371
00:43:19,034 --> 00:43:31,998
So just consider that point where somebody has said something which has, you know, annoyed you a bit, and how we keep repeating the insult over and over again, you know, until it really builds up into this huge fire, and you have to take an aspirin.

372
00:43:32,860 --> 00:43:38,510
And it's that, and then what you realize is that you're creating your own mental state.

373
00:43:39,065 --> 00:43:39,706
This is the point.

374
00:43:40,507 --> 00:43:43,632
And as soon as you realize that, well, you say, well, you know, do I have to do this?

375
00:43:43,733 --> 00:43:47,878
Do I have to, you know, turn something like that into a huge sort of drama?

376
00:43:48,780 --> 00:43:51,545
So, it's again this ability to forgive.

377
00:43:52,045 --> 00:44:05,527
And it helps to understand forgiveness, because now, having forgiven somebody, you realize that their suffering, either from callousness,

378
00:44:05,574 --> 00:44:11,543
Which leads to things like being lonely because nobody wants to know somebody who's sarcastic and audible.

379
00:44:13,204 --> 00:44:17,791
Or they're suffering themselves from feelings of guilt and shame.

380
00:44:17,811 --> 00:44:19,733
So that's your compassion.

381
00:44:20,355 --> 00:44:22,376
That's where your compassion comes in.

382
00:44:22,677 --> 00:44:27,364
So you also want to release them from their guilt and shame.

383
00:44:27,697 --> 00:44:33,565
So you offer them that opportunity by saying, you know, look, let's forget that, you know.

384
00:44:34,407 --> 00:44:37,371
Sorry it happened, but, you know, I forgive you and all that.

385
00:44:39,112 --> 00:44:48,726
And we do that when we realize that in the act of forgiving, we completely empty the heart of all that rubbish that we've burned up in there.

386
00:44:48,746 --> 00:44:48,846
Okay?

387
00:44:49,163 --> 00:44:51,786
And that the more you do it, the easier it's to do.

388
00:44:52,367 --> 00:45:00,298
It just becomes a habit so that there comes a point in our lives when even as the insult is given, the forgiveness arises with it.

389
00:45:00,739 --> 00:45:04,083
So there's never any pain around that.

390
00:45:04,103 --> 00:45:12,936
I mean, there's a lovely image the Buddha gives of somebody set upon by thieves and cut from limb to limb with their machete.

391
00:45:13,677 --> 00:45:18,764
And he says, if at any point hatred should arise or anger, they're no disciple of mine.

392
00:45:19,994 --> 00:45:23,697
When I once said this in the group, somebody said, well, the Buddha had a great sense of humour.

393
00:45:24,418 --> 00:45:28,702
I said, he might have had, but I think it actually means what he says.

394
00:45:31,005 --> 00:45:41,297
There is a way of receiving harm from somebody which doesn't bring that energy of anger from us.

395
00:45:41,717 --> 00:45:46,322
And that is where we begin to understand, really, the psychology of non-violence.

396
00:45:47,382 --> 00:45:59,382
It's only when you realize that nobody can actually make you angry, they can hurt your body, sticks and stones may hurt my bones and all that, but nobody can actually cause you internal suffering.

397
00:46:00,949 --> 00:46:07,217
And therefore, you're ready to, in a way, you absorb their anger.

398
00:46:07,737 --> 00:46:07,916
You see?

399
00:46:08,818 --> 00:46:09,900
You absorb their anger.

400
00:46:10,940 --> 00:46:18,588
And I'm sure you've experienced that in your life where somebody's come at you angrily and you've just said, oh, I'm sorry.

401
00:46:19,329 --> 00:46:24,375
And that I'm sorry, just actually taking responsibility for that moment just drains the anger out.

402
00:46:24,394 --> 00:46:29,960
Whereas if you'd have stood your ground and sort of butted them, then you'd have got into some sort of rage, a road rage or something.

403
00:46:31,072 --> 00:46:37,768
Now you may not have been guilty, it might have been somebody else who did it, but you prove that afterwards.

404
00:46:39,172 --> 00:46:44,766
But the important thing is to undermine the anger by receiving it, which is difficult.

405
00:46:45,527 --> 00:46:48,034
Our normal reaction is to defend ourselves.

406
00:46:50,257 --> 00:46:56,646
So this business of forgiving somebody, you see, we get confused.

407
00:46:56,666 --> 00:47:03,574
We think we're trying to forget it, you see, but trying to forget something is just another way of suppressing it.

408
00:47:03,594 --> 00:47:05,378
And we know that suppression doesn't do us any good.

409
00:47:05,878 --> 00:47:09,362
It just lies there as a turbulence within the mind, you know, within the heart.

410
00:47:10,264 --> 00:47:13,568
Sometimes we think we have to excuse them.

411
00:47:14,009 --> 00:47:16,130
But if somebody's robbed from us, they've robbed from us.

412
00:47:16,612 --> 00:47:17,413
It's all stopped.

413
00:47:17,983 --> 00:47:19,465
not to excuse it, they've been robbers.

414
00:47:21,228 --> 00:47:22,409
They've done an evil thing.

415
00:47:22,769 --> 00:47:28,838
You don't have to lessen their act, but you can forgive them for it.

416
00:47:28,858 --> 00:47:38,170
And you can ask for compensation for heaven's sake, if you feel it's right, without feeling that you're being vengeful.

417
00:47:40,411 --> 00:47:50,311
And sometimes we get a feeling of letting them off, almost in a sense condoning what they did, because we get into this business of punishment.

418
00:47:51,032 --> 00:47:56,242
You often hear these politicians saying, you know, they're putting people in prison for punishment and all that.

419
00:47:56,222 --> 00:48:04,670
Punishment doesn't hold any water in Buddhist understanding, because whenever you do something harmful, there's always some harmful results.

420
00:48:05,172 --> 00:48:07,092
So punishment is coming from some other center.

421
00:48:07,373 --> 00:48:13,298
It's coming from some center of where you're trying to frighten the person, so they'll never do that again.

422
00:48:13,619 --> 00:48:17,202
A sort of deterrence, you know, you cut your hand off if you steal.

423
00:48:17,342 --> 00:48:18,764
I mean, that works, is the point.

424
00:48:19,846 --> 00:48:23,208
But the punishment can't fit the crime.

425
00:48:23,527 --> 00:48:25,568
If it's the crime, then you'll have another go.

426
00:48:26,150 --> 00:48:31,775
So if the punishment is to be a deterrent, it's got to be something which really doesn't make the crime worth it.

427
00:48:32,536 --> 00:48:42,804
And they found this in these psychological tests where they've done this business of punishment and crime on a very low level, of course.

428
00:48:42,824 --> 00:48:48,990
And they found that the punishment has to really exceed the proceeds of the crime.

429
00:48:49,172 --> 00:48:49,652
It doesn't work.

430
00:48:51,708 --> 00:48:58,096
And of course, the other thing about punishment is that it's a way of slaking our vengefulness.

431
00:48:58,115 --> 00:48:59,197
And that doesn't work either.

432
00:48:59,757 --> 00:49:06,126
You know, people in the United States, in some states, you can see the murderer or the person who's murdered and all that.

433
00:49:06,507 --> 00:49:09,110
You can actually be at their execution.

434
00:49:10,612 --> 00:49:20,364
And the case is that people come out, like, you know, if one of your family members has been killed and all that, they come out, they've not been satisfied.

435
00:49:20,429 --> 00:49:25,137
They wanted it to be more painful, because that's the problem with revenge, isn't it?

436
00:49:25,677 --> 00:49:27,300
You can't satisfy hatred.

437
00:49:27,380 --> 00:49:29,043
Hatred eats on hatred.

438
00:49:29,103 --> 00:49:30,525
It feeds itself on hatred.

439
00:49:31,447 --> 00:49:37,838
So these people who actually want to see somebody suffering are simply growing in cruelty.

440
00:49:38,940 --> 00:49:41,643
They themselves are becoming more cruel than the criminals.

441
00:49:43,952 --> 00:49:47,115
So punishment doesn't hold water.

442
00:49:47,456 --> 00:50:06,536
So now, if you come to the understanding that you can't punish somebody, there's no point in eating your own heart out because somebody's harmed you, even going back to childhood, remember, then that process of forgiving somebody, and it helps to stand in the person's shoes.

443
00:50:07,177 --> 00:50:12,103
And we can do that more when we move into that third category, which is forgiving ourselves.

444
00:50:13,231 --> 00:50:21,202
and for what we've done to ourselves, you know, through whatever it might be, overeating, sex, drugs, rock and roll, all that sort of stuff.

445
00:50:21,222 --> 00:50:25,527
And forgiving ourselves is probably the most difficult thing to do.

446
00:50:25,567 --> 00:50:38,023
And it helps to understand that all our unwholesome actions have arisen because of a mistake.

447
00:50:38,344 --> 00:50:41,989
This is really a crucial, important understanding.

448
00:50:42,391 --> 00:50:50,023
The Buddha's word, he begins the process of our psychology with the word avijja, which means, translated as ignorance.

449
00:50:50,164 --> 00:50:53,730
But ignorance gives you the impression that you're at fault.

450
00:50:54,271 --> 00:50:56,474
You know, you should have known, you're just ignorant.

451
00:50:56,494 --> 00:50:56,976
But it's not.

452
00:50:57,356 --> 00:50:58,257
The word is neutral.

453
00:50:58,398 --> 00:50:59,400
You simply don't know.

454
00:50:59,420 --> 00:51:03,726
And out of that not knowing, there's been a mistake.

455
00:51:04,208 --> 00:51:06,811
And the mistake is who we really are.

456
00:51:06,791 --> 00:51:14,242
And the mistake is to believe that we really are human beings, that we really are this body, this mind, this heart.

457
00:51:14,842 --> 00:51:22,112
And by doing so, we then have to seek happiness, which is what all the heart wants, it wants peace and happiness, in the world.

458
00:51:22,913 --> 00:51:25,797
And how can you do that apart from accumulating things?

459
00:51:27,311 --> 00:51:29,014
The self has to feel safe.

460
00:51:29,315 --> 00:51:35,302
So it feels safe by having big bank accounts and having a very secure job and a very secure relationship.

461
00:51:35,322 --> 00:51:36,704
That's how it feels safe.

462
00:51:38,346 --> 00:51:43,532
But of course, as soon as you accumulate something, you're in conflict with other people who want what you've got.

463
00:51:45,496 --> 00:51:51,143
So the accumulation leads you immediately into a conflictual relationship with life.

464
00:51:51,545 --> 00:52:15,072
and then you find that you have to guard what you have and there's your fear and anxiety you have to get rid of people who seem to be undermining your happiness and so the whole battle is you know you enter into this whole battle that we call life now once you realize it's been a mistake

465
00:52:15,170 --> 00:52:34,291
then it takes away this feeling of being essentially evil and the knowledge is that just as this not knowing through the practice of vipassana through the practice of spiritual practice ends up at knowing as what we call wisdom

466
00:52:34,677 --> 00:52:39,150
From the heart's point of view, it's begun at a point of innocence.

467
00:52:39,170 --> 00:52:44,706
It didn't know it made a mistake, just like a child might light a match and burn a house down.

468
00:52:44,788 --> 00:52:47,235
It's a bit cruel to put it in jail.

469
00:52:48,682 --> 00:52:54,972
And that innocence is corrupted because of this wrong understanding, and then we end up with all this suffering.

470
00:52:55,432 --> 00:52:59,820
Then we get to a point where the suffering is so great we think, I'd better do some meditation.

471
00:52:59,840 --> 00:53:15,163
So then you start meditating and you come back on the process, you devolve, but that process is not back to an original ignorant, sorry, not knowing innocence, it now returns to a purity which matches the wisdom.

472
00:53:15,143 --> 00:53:21,594
That's why in the spiritual life you cannot grow in wisdom without growing in virtue.

473
00:53:22,115 --> 00:53:22,998
The two go together.

474
00:53:23,378 --> 00:53:27,806
The one is dependent on the mind and the other depends on the heart.

475
00:53:27,827 --> 00:53:27,907
See?

476
00:53:27,927 --> 00:53:36,864
So when you find yourself balking against the precepts, that is a measure to us of our delusion, of our mistake.

477
00:53:38,067 --> 00:53:38,146
See?

478
00:53:39,764 --> 00:54:04,202
so recognizing that is the first step and the second one is this business of there's no need to punish ourselves all we have to do is bear with the consequences of things that we've done wrong and that's all we have to do so I know somebody who just by a simple mistake it wasn't even wasn't anything

479
00:54:04,181 --> 00:54:12,331
evil or wrong or something, he just wanted to listen to music and he actually put the musical instrument he was playing, he put it right next to his ear.

480
00:54:12,893 --> 00:54:16,416
Well of course over a period of time it actually damaged his ear and gave him this terrible tinnitus.

481
00:54:17,297 --> 00:54:21,623
And then he had this struggle of hating it and fighting it and whatnot.

482
00:54:21,643 --> 00:54:28,873
And by undermining that process and just bearing with it and seeing it as a consequence of delusion,

483
00:54:29,393 --> 00:54:32,358
then it's just there as this little background whistling.

484
00:54:33,920 --> 00:54:36,425
It doesn't impinge upon his life anymore.

485
00:54:36,445 --> 00:54:40,192
And that's the same with people who are suddenly disabled in some way.

486
00:54:40,793 --> 00:54:52,632
See, if the disability is not accepted, if they're constantly fighting it, then they're just driving themselves into despair, and as you know, in some cases, suicide.

487
00:54:52,612 --> 00:55:03,119
But once it's accepted totally and it becomes part and parcel of the way they live, then it just doesn't undermine the quality of life.

488
00:55:03,139 --> 00:55:03,641
Simple as that.

489
00:55:04,423 --> 00:55:08,715
So this process of self-forgiveness is really important.

490
00:55:10,449 --> 00:55:12,431
So that's the process that we're going through.

491
00:55:12,492 --> 00:55:31,394
We're developing the heart of goodwill, developing the heart of compassion, and then we turn it through the process of forgiveness to correct our relationship to the world where there's been harm, either done to us or by us to others or by us to ourselves.

492
00:55:31,847 --> 00:55:41,666
And remember that this, you can't do all this in a weekend, this is a process that you have to take with you into your daily life.

493
00:55:42,768 --> 00:55:50,362
And I think you'll find that the more you practice it, you get the benefits, tremendous, tremendous benefits.

494
00:55:52,739 --> 00:55:55,922
And it's not as though you have to go at it all the time.

495
00:55:57,105 --> 00:56:07,498
It's the constant little bits, like in the morning, you know, and during the day when you feel a bit upset about something, to immediately go into the process of forgiveness.

496
00:56:08,159 --> 00:56:15,507
And it's just those little points that just very slowly, over a period of time, just change us completely.

497
00:56:17,190 --> 00:56:22,257
It's the persistence of practice that's important, doing it whenever the occasion arises.

498
00:56:25,762 --> 00:56:29,010
So I think that draws me to the end of my little homily.

499
00:56:29,030 --> 00:56:32,177
A bit longer than I thought, but there we are.

500
00:56:32,197 --> 00:56:34,643
So I can only hope my words have been of some assistance.

501
00:56:35,206 --> 00:56:40,818
May you be liberated from all suffering sooner rather than later.

